00:33:36,157 --> 00:33:38,286
You're right. Starting from Line Five.

980
00:33:38,287 --> 00:33:39,856
Line Nine would be incredible.

981
00:33:39,857 --> 00:33:41,826
It depends on whether there's a bunker or not.

982
00:33:41,827 --> 00:33:44,767
- If a nuclear bomb goes off, - Yes.

983
00:33:45,127 --> 00:33:46,697
isn't a few stations not enough?

984
00:33:46,797 --> 00:33:47,866
- Don't you have to...
- Should I walk further?

985
00:33:47,867 --> 00:33:48,936
go all the way...

986
00:33:48,937 --> 00:33:50,136
- to find...
- But...

987
00:33:50,137 --> 00:33:51,206
It's not as far as you might think.

988
00:33:51,207 --> 00:33:52,437
- Really?
- Yes.

989
00:33:52,637 --> 00:33:55,006
If you listen closely to the civil defense broadcast...

990
00:33:55,007 --> 00:33:56,907
This is actually a side note,

991
00:33:57,207 --> 00:33:59,247
but in the civil defense broadcast,

992
00:33:59,447 --> 00:34:01,876
there is someone who explains...

993
00:34:01,877 --> 00:34:04,416
- the evacuation procedures, right?
- Yes.

994
00:34:04,417 --> 00:34:05,516
I'm sure you didn't listen carefully,

995
00:34:05,517 --> 00:34:06,786
but I actually recorded that.

996
00:34:06,787 --> 00:34:08,357
- What?
- Really?

997
00:34:08,717 --> 00:34:10,256
(2025 Civil Defense Air Raid Drill Live Broadcast)

998
00:34:10,257 --> 00:34:11,726
(2025 August 20, 2pm)

999
00:34:11,727 --> 00:34:13,226
(Emergency Procedures for Air Raid Alerts)

1000
00:34:13,227 --> 00:34:14,727
(Seung Byeong's voice in the actual broadcast)

1001
00:34:14,957 --> 00:34:16,196
I did it last year...

1002
00:34:16,197 --> 00:34:17,426
- and the year before, - Civil defense?

1003
00:34:17,427 --> 00:34:18,526
- so try listening to it.
- The civil defense training.

1004
00:34:18,527 --> 00:34:21,066
- So how far do we need to walk out?
- Right.

1005
00:34:21,067 --> 00:34:24,106
Usually, just a few kilometers away...

1006
00:34:24,107 --> 00:34:25,136
will increase the chances...

1007
00:34:25,137 --> 00:34:26,336
- of survival.
- The chances of survival...

1008
00:34:26,337 --> 00:34:27,836
In the broadcast,

1009
00:34:27,837 --> 00:34:29,136
they will tell you where it fell,

1010
00:34:29,137 --> 00:34:30,806
which way the wind is heading,

1011
00:34:30,807 --> 00:34:32,976
and which way you need to head.

1012
00:34:32,977 --> 00:34:34,947
Then you're sacrificing yourself?

1013
00:34:35,177 --> 00:34:37,146
We will be at the subway station, but you need to broadcast it.

1014
00:34:37,147 --> 00:34:38,847
- I know.
- Above the ground.

1015
00:34:39,117 --> 00:34:40,787
The broadcast should be done from a safe location.

1016
00:34:41,357 --> 00:34:42,956
That's what we want to know!

1017
00:34:42,957 --> 00:34:44,926
Where is that place, Seung Byeong?

1018
00:34:44,927 --> 00:34:46,856
- Tell us where you will be!
- Yes.

1019
00:34:46,857 --> 00:34:48,056
- Take us with you.
- That's the safest place.

1020
00:34:48,057 --> 00:34:49,196
The place where you can be safe...

1021
00:34:49,197 --> 00:34:50,496
while you are broadcasting.

1022
00:34:50,497 --> 00:34:52,626
- Yes, we need to go there.
- Yes.

1023
00:34:52,627 --> 00:34:53,666
- Seung Byeong has...
- The broadcast should be done...

1024
00:34:53,667 --> 00:34:54,696
- to be safe first to guide us.
- in the safe place.

1025
00:34:54,697 --> 00:34:55,697
- Yes.
- Right.

1026
00:34:55,698 --> 00:34:56,896
- He has to be safe.
- That's right.

1027
00:34:56,897 --> 00:34:58,966
- We need to get his number.
- Yes.

1028
00:34:58,967 --> 00:35:00,036
- I would ask...
- Yes. I can get it...

1029
00:35:00,037 --> 00:35:01,076
- because he's like my brother.
- Then...

1030
00:35:01,077 --> 00:35:03,436
I'm just curious, but sometimes,

1031
00:35:03,437 --> 00:35:06,147
there are rumors about a place in the desert in the US...

1032
00:35:06,777 --> 00:35:07,846
where there is...

1033
00:35:07,847 --> 00:35:08,876
- an underground bunker.
- Right.

1034
00:35:08,877 --> 00:35:11,086
They say there's a luxury bunker...

1035
00:35:11,087 --> 00:35:12,087
They say they can live there for a few years.

1036
00:35:12,088 --> 00:35:13,786
- Right.
- where you can survive...

1037
00:35:13,787 --> 00:35:15,886
for months and years.

1038
00:35:15,887 --> 00:35:17,526
- It's 30 million dollars.
- There are advertisements...

1039
00:35:17,527 --> 00:35:18,686
- Yes.
- offering sales...

1040
00:35:18,687 --> 00:35:19,687
- for those places.
- Yes.

1041
00:35:19,987 --> 00:35:22,627
Is it really safe in there, even with a nuclear explosion?

1042
00:35:22,927 --> 00:35:26,496
Sure. Those places have already met the required standards,

1043
00:35:26,497 --> 00:35:28,736
and they have all the food and drinks ready.

1044
00:35:28,737 --> 00:35:32,066
Most importantly, they already have the filters perfectly designed...

1045
00:35:32,067 --> 00:35:35,106
to keep contaminated air and other pollutants from getting inside,

1046
00:35:35,107 --> 00:35:36,607
so they can hold out for quite a long time.

1047
00:35:37,377 --> 00:35:40,746
Those were mainly built in the United States and Europe...

1048
00:35:40,747 --> 00:35:43,476
when the threat of nuclear war was much greater.

1049
00:35:43,477 --> 00:35:45,846
They were designed to last...

1050
00:35:45,847 --> 00:35:48,586
for at least 3 to 5 years.

1051
00:35:48,587 --> 00:35:49,886
- Gosh.
- Three to five years?

1052
00:35:49,887 --> 00:35:53,627
So, if a nuclear weapon is expected to strike,

1053
00:35:54,457 --> 00:35:57,067
how many hours in advance can we know?

1054
00:35:57,567 --> 00:35:58,567
For that...

1055
00:35:58,897 --> 00:36:00,666
We can know about ten minutes beforehand.

1056
00:36:00,667 --> 00:36:01,736
- Gosh.
- Gosh.

1057
00:36:01,737 --> 00:36:03,036
- We can't do anything.
- Even in today's world?

1058
00:36:03,037 --> 00:36:06,636
Sure. We may be able to know earlier if we see them...

1059
00:36:06,637 --> 00:36:08,976
bringing out the missile from underground...

1060
00:36:08,977 --> 00:36:11,606
- and preparing to launch, - Really?

1061
00:36:11,607 --> 00:36:15,847
but we can't predict which direction they are targeting.

1062
00:36:16,217 --> 00:36:17,646
So that's why once it's launched,

1063
00:36:17,647 --> 00:36:19,447
the first priority is to intercept it.

1064
00:36:19,747 --> 00:36:23,586
But still, since South Korea is very small,

1065
00:36:23,587 --> 00:36:26,886
we can only know about 10 or 15 minutes in advance.

1066
00:36:26,887 --> 00:36:30,157
If a missile carrying a nuclear weapon is launched,

1067
00:36:30,597 --> 00:36:33,096
- can it still be intercepted?
- Sure, it can.

1068
00:36:33,097 --> 00:36:35,336
If it is intercepted,

1069
00:36:35,337 --> 00:36:37,437
will there still be nuclear fallout...

1070
00:36:38,137 --> 00:36:39,406
from that?

1071
00:36:39,407 --> 00:36:41,136
- When it is directly hit, - Yes.

1072
00:36:41,137 --> 00:36:43,407
it may not cause a nuclear explosion.

1073
00:36:44,677 --> 00:36:47,316
It could simply fall without functioning,

1074
00:36:47,317 --> 00:36:48,516
so we need to see.

1075
00:36:48,517 --> 00:36:50,616
You might think that when it is hit,

1076
00:36:50,617 --> 00:36:51,986
- there will be an explosion, right?
- Yes.

1077
00:36:51,987 --> 00:36:56,286
That's not it. The nuclear reaction occurs when the warhead reaches...

1078
00:36:56,287 --> 00:36:58,526
its calculated target and the necessary conditions...

1079
00:36:58,527 --> 00:37:00,596
for detonation are satisfied.

1080
00:37:00,597 --> 00:37:02,196
If it is intercepted and exploded,

1081
00:37:02,197 --> 00:37:03,696
the nuclear reaction does not occur.

1082
00:37:03,697 --> 00:37:05,726
- Gosh.
- That's good.

1083
00:37:05,727 --> 00:37:07,666
Make sure to intercept it successfully.

1084
00:37:07,667 --> 00:37:10,097
- Yes.
- He explained it so well.

1085
00:37:10,567 --> 00:37:12,667
Then, in the movies,

1086
00:37:12,967 --> 00:37:14,237
- they hack the program...
- Yes.

1087
00:37:14,477 --> 00:37:16,336
- and change the route.
- That's right.

1088
00:37:16,337 --> 00:37:18,176
- They hack it.
- To change it.

1089
00:37:18,177 --> 00:37:19,546
- That's right.
- They change the route.

1090
00:37:19,547 --> 00:37:20,547
- They hack it like that.
- And follow it.

1091
00:37:20,548 --> 00:37:22,616
- They chase it.
- Is it possible in real life?

1092
00:37:22,617 --> 00:37:24,017
It's not possible in real life.

1093
00:37:24,517 --> 00:37:26,687
Especially with nuclear missiles,

1094
00:37:26,787 --> 00:37:28,386
the launch process is actually more primitive...

1095
00:37:28,387 --> 00:37:29,987
- than you would think.
- Really?

1096
00:37:30,157 --> 00:37:32,056
It's designed like that on purpose as well,

1097
00:37:32,057 --> 00:37:34,796
but generally, the nuclear missile systems we use today...

1098
00:37:34,797 --> 00:37:39,396
were built about 50 years ago.

1099
00:37:39,397 --> 00:37:42,996
If the president orders a launch on another country,

1100
00:37:42,997 --> 00:37:45,206
there are people stationed at the base...

1101
00:37:45,207 --> 00:37:48,606
who have to carry out the procedure both at once.

1102
00:37:48,607 --> 00:37:49,906
You can see that in the movies.

1103
00:37:49,907 --> 00:37:52,477
They have to turn the keys at the same time in order to work.

1104
00:37:53,377 --> 00:37:56,216
Like so, many of the systems won't even operate at all...

1105
00:37:56,217 --> 00:37:58,116
unless there is human involvement.

1106
00:37:58,117 --> 00:38:00,316
Since they were built long ago,

1107
00:38:00,317 --> 00:38:02,756
changing the course mid-flight...

1108
00:38:02,757 --> 00:38:04,556
- It's impossible to upgrade?
- to control is impossible.

1109
00:38:04,557 --> 00:38:05,726
You're right.

1110
00:38:05,727 --> 00:38:07,496
The last part is...

1111
00:38:07,497 --> 00:38:09,726
Presentation Class.

1112
00:38:09,727 --> 00:38:12,526
Yong Han and Seung Byeong have prepared...

1113
00:38:12,527 --> 00:38:16,167
a Special Memorial Day Lecture for today.

1114
00:38:17,067 --> 00:38:19,867
Yong Han will talk about the Korean War.

1115
00:38:20,137 --> 00:38:21,506
- The Korean War.
- Yes.

1116
00:38:21,507 --> 00:38:24,307
I, from a science and engineering perspective, will talk about...

1117
00:38:24,607 --> 00:38:28,216
the weapons and technologies that were developed from that time.

1118
00:38:28,217 --> 00:38:29,877
That's the two most interesting topics.

1119
00:38:30,347 --> 00:38:32,047
Attention, applaud.

1120
00:38:33,147 --> 00:38:34,816
(They are ready to fall into the lecture.)

1121
00:38:34,817 --> 00:38:37,926
It's an event that can never be left out of the history of South Korea.

1122
00:38:37,927 --> 00:38:40,286
I will talk about the Korean War, which still involves a lot...

1123
00:38:40,287 --> 00:38:42,756
of people who experienced its hardships until today...

1124
00:38:42,757 --> 00:38:46,697
and which remains something we must continue to remember.

1125
00:38:47,467 --> 00:38:53,267
(1950, June 25, 4am)

1126
00:38:53,607 --> 00:38:56,706
(The Korean War began with North Korea's...)

1127
00:38:56,707 --> 00:38:59,007
(surprise attack on South Korea.)

1128
00:38:59,407 --> 00:39:02,046
(South Korean military casualties, Fatalities: 137,000)

1129
00:39:02,047 --> 00:39:04,687
(Injured: 450,000, Missing or captured: 30,000)

1130
00:39:05,017 --> 00:39:08,757
(Separated families: 10 million, Orphaned: 100,000)

1131
00:39:09,087 --> 00:39:13,727
(The Korean War set our history back to the Stone Age.)

1132
00:39:13,897 --> 00:39:17,927
(A tragedy that changed the fate of the Korean Peninsula)

1133
00:39:18,797 --> 00:39:22,136
I will focus on the strategic and tactical aspects...

1134
00:39:22,137 --> 00:39:24,306
that are not widely known,

1135
00:39:24,307 --> 00:39:26,506
and the key historical lessons it offers.

1136
00:39:26,507 --> 00:39:28,537
The first chapter is "The Fateful Three Days."

1137
00:39:28,677 --> 00:39:29,677
(Im Yong Han's Korean War Master)

1138
00:39:29,937 --> 00:39:33,506
(Chapter 1: The Outbreak of War and the Fateful 3 Days)

1139
00:39:33,507 --> 00:39:36,747
One of the most shocking events of the Korean War...

1140
00:39:36,917 --> 00:39:38,086
was not just the surprise invasion itself,

1141
00:39:38,087 --> 00:39:40,247
- but the fall of Seoul on June 28.
- Falling of Seoul?

1142
00:39:40,387 --> 00:39:41,887
It fell in just three days.

1143
00:39:42,487 --> 00:39:46,256
(The heroic People's Army completely liberated Seoul...)

1144
00:39:46,257 --> 00:39:49,926
(from the colonial rule of the US imperialist aggressors...)

1145
00:39:49,927 --> 00:39:51,996
(just 3 days after launching its counteroffensive.)

1146
00:39:51,997 --> 00:39:53,996
But those three fateful days turned out to be...

1147
00:39:53,997 --> 00:39:55,997
a decisive turning point...

1148
00:39:56,137 --> 00:39:58,166
of the Korean War.

1149
00:39:58,167 --> 00:39:59,467
(A decisive turning point of the Korean War)

1150
00:40:00,007 --> 00:40:02,776
At the time, the North Korean forces had planned to occupy...

1151
00:40:02,777 --> 00:40:04,847
this entire area by around July 25.

1152
00:40:05,247 --> 00:40:07,177
Why were they in such a hurry?

1153
00:40:07,617 --> 00:40:09,377
- To avoid the US getting involved.
- That's right.

1154
00:40:09,747 --> 00:40:13,287
The US forces would have to cross the Pacific to intervene,

1155
00:40:13,487 --> 00:40:14,956
and that would take at least a month for them to arrive.

1156
00:40:14,957 --> 00:40:17,057
So the plan was designed so that they'd have occupied...

1157
00:40:17,217 --> 00:40:19,386
the entire country by around July 23.

1158
00:40:19,387 --> 00:40:21,596
(North Korea's Plan for Invasion of South Korea)

1159
00:40:21,597 --> 00:40:23,797
(North Korean Preemptive Strike Plan)

1160
00:40:23,997 --> 00:40:25,866
(Phase 1: Neutralization of the Main South Korean Forces, 5 days)

1161
00:40:25,867 --> 00:40:26,896
(Phase 2: Neutralization...)

1162
00:40:26,897 --> 00:40:28,336
(of South Korean Reinforcements, 19 days)

1163
00:40:28,337 --> 00:40:30,236
(Phase 3: Southward Advance...)

1164
00:40:30,237 --> 00:40:33,736
(and Elimination of South Korean Forces, 29 days)

1165
00:40:33,737 --> 00:40:35,907
The most important plan of North Korea forces...

1166
00:40:36,137 --> 00:40:38,507
was to capture Seoul in three days.

1167
00:40:38,647 --> 00:40:41,517
Capturing it in three days wasn't the important part.

1168
00:40:42,317 --> 00:40:44,046
The goal wasn't just to break through here...

1169
00:40:44,047 --> 00:40:47,017
and capture Seoul in three days.

1170
00:40:47,517 --> 00:40:49,856
The goal was total annihilation of the South Korean forces...

1171
00:40:49,857 --> 00:40:51,227
in this area.

1172
00:40:52,227 --> 00:40:53,656
That was the key point.

1173
00:40:53,657 --> 00:40:55,126
(Total annihilation of South Korean forces in Seoul)

1174
00:40:55,127 --> 00:40:58,327
At the time, the South Korean army had eight divisions.

1175
00:40:58,527 --> 00:40:59,796
It was eight divisions in name only.

1176
00:40:59,797 --> 00:41:01,296
The four rear divisions were operating...

1177
00:41:01,297 --> 00:41:02,767
at less than 50 percent combat strength.

1178
00:41:03,237 --> 00:41:05,006
So the four frontline divisions accounted...

1179
00:41:05,007 --> 00:41:06,767
for nearly 70 percent of the army's actual combat power.

1180
00:41:07,377 --> 00:41:08,936
If those forces were destroyed,

1181
00:41:08,937 --> 00:41:11,047
everything behind them would be virtually undefended.

1182
00:41:11,307 --> 00:41:12,976
From that point on, occupying...

1183
00:41:12,977 --> 00:41:14,647
- the Korean Peninsula by July 24...
- Right.

1184
00:41:14,777 --> 00:41:16,577
would have been largely a matter of advancing on foot.

1185
00:41:16,917 --> 00:41:18,947
In essence, the plan was to annihilate the combat power...

1186
00:41:19,117 --> 00:41:20,857
of the South Korean army right here.

1187
00:41:21,117 --> 00:41:23,357
There's a division called the North Korean Sixth Division.

1188
00:41:23,887 --> 00:41:26,287
It was made up entirely of the Eighth Route Army.

1189
00:41:26,857 --> 00:41:29,556
There was the Chinese Civil War...

1190
00:41:29,557 --> 00:41:31,197
between the Communists and the Nationalists.

1191
00:41:31,297 --> 00:41:33,997
The Communist military forces here were known as the Eighth Route Army.

1192
00:41:34,997 --> 00:41:36,066
These soldiers...

1193
00:41:36,067 --> 00:41:37,907
- had combat experience, - Right.

1194
00:41:38,107 --> 00:41:41,137
so they were transferred into the North Korean army.

1195
00:41:41,707 --> 00:41:44,146
About half of the North Korean forces...

1196
00:41:44,147 --> 00:41:45,407
were made up of former Eighth Route Army veterans.

1197
00:41:45,777 --> 00:41:46,946
- Their experience...
- They had experience.

1198
00:41:46,947 --> 00:41:49,477
Their combat experience was almost unimaginable.

1199
00:41:50,177 --> 00:41:52,186
The Sixth Division...

1200
00:41:52,187 --> 00:41:54,117
consisted entirely of former Eighth Route Army veterans.

1201
00:41:54,487 --> 00:41:56,286
- They were the most formidable.
- They were the most formidable.

1202
00:41:56,287 --> 00:41:58,087
So the strongest division...

1203
00:41:58,557 --> 00:42:00,427
was sent across near Gimpo...

1204
00:42:00,557 --> 00:42:03,027
to circle around toward Yeongdeungpo.

1205
00:42:03,857 --> 00:42:05,426
At the time, the key crossing points over the Han River...

1206
00:42:05,427 --> 00:42:07,466
were crossing over Mapo...

1207
00:42:07,467 --> 00:42:09,297
and Yeouido to come here,

1208
00:42:09,537 --> 00:42:12,437
then the Han River Railway Bridge and the pedestrian bridge.

1209
00:42:12,667 --> 00:42:15,237
This route was important, but this was also a key route.

1210
00:42:16,077 --> 00:42:18,206
So they moved in like this and blocked this area.

1211
00:42:18,207 --> 00:42:19,207
Goodness.

1212
00:42:19,208 --> 00:42:22,617
This meant that North Korean forces would advance from the front,

1213
00:42:22,747 --> 00:42:25,986
and our army would be trapped between the river...

1214
00:42:25,987 --> 00:42:28,286
and the North Korean Sixth Division, and get completely wiped out.

1215
00:42:28,287 --> 00:42:29,487
That was the key point.

1216
00:42:29,917 --> 00:42:31,726
The Sixth Division was going to push down.

1217
00:42:31,727 --> 00:42:34,957
What date had they set for reaching Yeongdeungpo?

1218
00:42:35,227 --> 00:42:36,297
July 1.

1219
00:42:36,557 --> 00:42:37,627
June 30.

1220
00:42:38,497 --> 00:42:39,866
It was June 26.

1221
00:42:39,867 --> 00:42:41,897
- In just 1 day?
- In just 1 day?

1222
00:42:42,267 --> 00:42:44,237
They thought they were basically walking into an empty house.

1223
00:42:44,537 --> 00:42:45,866
That's exactly right. They basically thought it would be...

1224
00:42:45,867 --> 00:42:47,236
- like walking into an empty house.
- Right.

1225
00:42:47,237 --> 00:42:49,407
You shouldn't plan a war like this.

1226
00:42:50,137 --> 00:42:51,777
They were also...

1227
00:42:51,907 --> 00:42:54,817
- They were in a rush.
- very concerned about the US.

1228
00:42:55,217 --> 00:42:58,486
In fact, since 1946, North Korea had repeatedly expressed...

1229
00:42:58,487 --> 00:43:01,487
its intention to invade South Korea to the Soviet Union,

1230
00:43:01,757 --> 00:43:03,157
but they kept advising against it.

1231
00:43:03,257 --> 00:43:05,327
- "But what if the US intervenes?"
- Right.

1232
00:43:05,587 --> 00:43:08,727
So they kept delaying it.

1233
00:43:08,857 --> 00:43:09,996
But later, they said,

1234
00:43:09,997 --> 00:43:11,627
"Why don't we finish it before the US steps in?"

1235
00:43:12,167 --> 00:43:14,667
So to go with that plan,

1236
00:43:14,897 --> 00:43:18,107
they set an ambitious timetable to come here by June 26.

1237
00:43:18,607 --> 00:43:20,666
But even that wasn't enough.

1238
00:43:20,667 --> 00:43:22,737
The well-known Sixth Division of the South Korean army here...

1239
00:43:23,137 --> 00:43:24,846
The North Korean Second Corps were going to destroy...

1240
00:43:24,847 --> 00:43:26,547
the South Korean Sixth Division in the Chuncheon region.

1241
00:43:26,977 --> 00:43:29,277
They would crush them here and move here...

1242
00:43:29,577 --> 00:43:32,687
and establish a second blocking line in Suwon.

1243
00:43:33,387 --> 00:43:35,957
The planned date for this move was June 30.

1244
00:43:37,387 --> 00:43:39,257
It was an ambitious plan.

1245
00:43:39,757 --> 00:43:42,727
And that's how the battle began here.

1246
00:43:43,827 --> 00:43:46,396
A major issue in the South Korean army at the time was that...

1247
00:43:46,397 --> 00:43:48,536
roughly a third of personnel were away on leave or pass.

1248
00:43:48,537 --> 00:43:49,836
Right.

1249
00:43:49,837 --> 00:43:51,236
This keeps getting mentioned,

1250
00:43:51,237 --> 00:43:52,937
but an even more serious issue...

1251
00:43:53,207 --> 00:43:55,036
was that nearly half of all trucks, vehicles, heavy weapons,

1252
00:43:55,037 --> 00:43:56,506
and machine guns...

1253
00:43:56,507 --> 00:43:58,947
had been pulled out of service for maintenance and repair.

1254
00:43:59,877 --> 00:44:01,816
To continue fighting,

1255
00:44:01,817 --> 00:44:03,777
ammunition had to be continuously supplied.

1256
00:44:03,977 --> 00:44:05,187
But there were no vehicles.

1257
00:44:05,447 --> 00:44:07,386
So they couldn't properly distribute shells and other supplies.

1258
00:44:07,387 --> 00:44:09,657
Why was so much of it out of service at the same time?

1259
00:44:09,857 --> 00:44:11,086
That's a mystery.

1260
00:44:11,087 --> 00:44:12,386
Did something happen that day?

1261
00:44:12,387 --> 00:44:15,396
Overall, the country was not well prepared for war.

1262
00:44:15,397 --> 00:44:18,026
In other words, the forces that were actually deployed...

1263
00:44:18,027 --> 00:44:20,296
were not in a condition to fight a war.

1264
00:44:20,297 --> 00:44:22,096
(Pre-War Military Comparison)

1265
00:44:22,097 --> 00:44:23,837
For example, this was the most basic issue.

1266
00:44:24,607 --> 00:44:25,867
The front line was very long.

1267
00:44:26,137 --> 00:44:28,907
Today, the 248km armistice line...

1268
00:44:29,177 --> 00:44:30,677
is defended by dozens of divisions,

1269
00:44:31,407 --> 00:44:33,807
but at the time, South Korea had only four divisions.

1270
00:44:34,317 --> 00:44:36,417
So how could four divisions possibly defend...

1271
00:44:36,817 --> 00:44:38,786
- such a wide front?
- How could they?

1272
00:44:38,787 --> 00:44:39,917
(4 divisions defended the long front line.)

1273
00:44:40,147 --> 00:44:41,656
In the end, they had to defend the forces in a front...

1274
00:44:41,657 --> 00:44:43,787
that far exceeded their available forces.

1275
00:44:44,017 --> 00:44:45,127
How do you do that?

1276
00:44:45,327 --> 00:44:46,487
Reserve divisions in the rear.

1277
00:44:46,957 --> 00:44:48,227
Reserve divisions in the rear.

1278
00:44:48,357 --> 00:44:50,296
He's become an expert in war.

1279
00:44:50,297 --> 00:44:51,427
(Approved as a war expert)

1280
00:44:51,527 --> 00:44:53,167
So what you do here..

1281
00:44:53,567 --> 00:44:54,836
is to deploy the divisions like this.

1282
00:44:54,837 --> 00:44:56,036
(Deploying forces to the front and rear)

1283
00:44:56,037 --> 00:44:58,167
If the forces come and hit here,

1284
00:44:58,537 --> 00:44:59,666
they shouldn't move.

1285
00:44:59,667 --> 00:45:01,176
If they move,

1286
00:45:01,177 --> 00:45:02,707
the enemies will come through here.

1287
00:45:02,977 --> 00:45:04,447
The unit behind should come and fight.

1288
00:45:06,047 --> 00:45:07,746
Even if they have twice the number of troops...

1289
00:45:07,747 --> 00:45:09,617
Let's say this unit comes here and this one here.

1290
00:45:09,847 --> 00:45:12,047
If one moves, the one behind comes to fight.

1291
00:45:13,547 --> 00:45:15,387
If a forward unit collapses and falls back,

1292
00:45:15,957 --> 00:45:18,027
the idea is that it withdraws,

1293
00:45:18,257 --> 00:45:19,587
and then once the enemy advances,

1294
00:45:19,727 --> 00:45:21,256
this unit can go around and strike them.

1295
00:45:21,257 --> 00:45:22,326
(A system in which rear units move up and strike the enemy)

1296
00:45:22,327 --> 00:45:24,927
This is what efficient force utilization looks like.

1297
00:45:25,227 --> 00:45:26,367
Even with limited manpower.

1298
00:45:26,697 --> 00:45:27,697
But how were our forces...

1299
00:45:27,698 --> 00:45:29,496
- actually positioned back then?
- How were they positioned?

1300
00:45:29,497 --> 00:45:31,437
They were positioned like this.

1301
00:45:32,807 --> 00:45:34,006
(Exclaiming)

1302
00:45:34,007 --> 00:45:35,137
What?

1303
00:45:35,377 --> 00:45:36,707
They were positioned in a line.

1304
00:45:37,847 --> 00:45:40,206
- They had no plan.
- If the enemy...

1305
00:45:40,207 --> 00:45:42,876
comes around to hit from the side, it would be the end.

1306
00:45:42,877 --> 00:45:46,647
- Right. They shouldn't do that.
- They weren't prepared for war.

1307
00:45:47,217 --> 00:45:49,517
So they came down in that situation.

1308
00:45:49,887 --> 00:45:52,187
They succeeded in coming Seoul in three days.

1309
00:45:52,487 --> 00:45:55,726
At the time, some South Korean soldiers...

1310
00:45:55,727 --> 00:45:57,597
at the front...

1311
00:45:57,667 --> 00:46:00,097
did retreat or collapse,

1312
00:46:00,367 --> 00:46:03,397
but about a third fought with their lives on the line.

1313
00:46:04,607 --> 00:46:08,037
They gave their lives just to hold out for a minute.

1314
00:46:08,577 --> 00:46:10,677
Those who could hold on did so.

1315
00:46:11,107 --> 00:46:13,377
So they defended this place with their lives.

1316
00:46:13,777 --> 00:46:16,116
The North Koreans did capture Seoul within three days,

1317
00:46:16,117 --> 00:46:17,887
but their losses...

1318
00:46:18,247 --> 00:46:20,817
were more than 30 percent higher than expected.

1319
00:46:20,917 --> 00:46:22,717
The forces were completely worn out.

1320
00:46:23,357 --> 00:46:24,726
The most important thing was that...

1321
00:46:24,727 --> 00:46:26,087
they had to go to Yeongdeungpo in a day,

1322
00:46:26,657 --> 00:46:29,696
but the US decided to enter the war on June 27.

1323
00:46:29,697 --> 00:46:30,996
(Chapter 1: The Outbreak of War and the Fateful 3 Days)

1324
00:46:30,997 --> 00:46:34,266
(Chapter 2: US Intervention and the Nakdong River Defense Line)

1325
00:46:34,267 --> 00:46:36,236
What we commonly know...

1326
00:46:36,237 --> 00:46:38,706
is that they submitted to the UN Nations Security Council...

1327
00:46:38,707 --> 00:46:40,736
to assemble a UN coalition force.

1328
00:46:40,737 --> 00:46:43,306
(The principal body responsible for maintaining peace...)

1329
00:46:43,307 --> 00:46:45,877
(and security among its member states)

1330
00:46:46,447 --> 00:46:49,546
(The present situation is a serious one...)

1331
00:46:49,547 --> 00:46:53,386
(and is a threat to international peace.)

1332
00:46:53,387 --> 00:46:57,256
(We must take steps necessary to reestablish peace...)

1333
00:46:57,257 --> 00:47:00,027
(in that area.)

1334
00:47:00,187 --> 00:47:02,356
(But the formation of a UN force required the approval...)

1335
00:47:02,357 --> 00:47:04,526
(of all 5 permanent members of the Security Council.)

1336
00:47:04,527 --> 00:47:07,766
But the Soviet Union chose to abstain.

1337
00:47:07,767 --> 00:47:09,696
Had they exercised their veto,

1338
00:47:09,697 --> 00:47:11,837
a UN force would likely never have been formed.

1339
00:47:12,207 --> 00:47:16,136
So out of diplomatic considerations, the Soviet Union abstained,

1340
00:47:16,137 --> 00:47:17,336
and that allowed the UN force to be formed.

1341
00:47:17,337 --> 00:47:18,777
That's what we know.

1342
00:47:19,047 --> 00:47:21,516
Actually, the US mattered more than the UN.

1343
00:47:21,517 --> 00:47:23,377
Nearly 90 percent of the combat power came from the US military.

1344
00:47:23,577 --> 00:47:26,916
The US decided to intervene independently of the UN.

1345
00:47:26,917 --> 00:47:28,016
(The US decided to intervene independently of the UN.)

1346
00:47:28,017 --> 00:47:32,526
(Korea is a small country thousands of miles away.)

1347
00:47:32,527 --> 00:47:35,727
(But what is happening there is important to every American.)

1348
00:47:36,027 --> 00:47:39,926
(We are united in detesting communist slavery.)

1349
00:47:39,927 --> 00:47:43,196
(We know that the cost of freedom is high.)

1350
00:47:43,197 --> 00:47:45,566
(But we are determined to preserve our freedom, )

1351
00:47:45,567 --> 00:47:47,937
(no matter what the cost.)

1352
00:47:48,577 --> 00:47:51,106
The UN Security Council decided on June 28,

1353
00:47:51,107 --> 00:47:54,777
but by June 27, the US had already decided to intervene.

1354
00:47:55,147 --> 00:47:57,947
They sent the units in Japan to intervene.

1355
00:47:58,387 --> 00:48:00,417
Since it was urgent, the aircraft took off first.

1356
00:48:01,087 --> 00:48:03,017
Many fighter aircraft took off.

1357
00:48:03,587 --> 00:48:06,057
They gained air superiority.

1358
00:48:06,557 --> 00:48:08,796
North Korea hadn't anticipated this...

1359
00:48:08,797 --> 00:48:10,727
and had no anti-aircraft defenses.

1360
00:48:11,127 --> 00:48:12,326
They had to go to Yeongdeungpo by June 26,

1361
00:48:12,327 --> 00:48:13,366
but since the Air Force came,

1362
00:48:13,367 --> 00:48:14,567
they couldn't move during the day.

1363
00:48:16,067 --> 00:48:19,336
They ended up getting Yeongdeungpo on July 3.

1364
00:48:19,337 --> 00:48:20,607
It got delayed a lot.

1365
00:48:20,937 --> 00:48:24,337
With all these factors combined, they arrived here on July 3.

1366
00:48:24,707 --> 00:48:26,846
So they captured Seoul on June 28,

1367
00:48:26,847 --> 00:48:29,347
but since they didn't come, the units here couldn't move.

1368
00:48:30,047 --> 00:48:31,547
We gained more than three days.

1369
00:48:31,747 --> 00:48:33,646
These days, there are various theories...

1370
00:48:33,647 --> 00:48:36,056
about "the mystery of the Korean War,"

1371
00:48:36,057 --> 00:48:37,687
questioning why North Korean forces didn't advance further in Seoul.

1372
00:48:37,987 --> 00:48:40,887
There was no big reason. Things didn't go according to plan.

1373
00:48:42,427 --> 00:48:43,857
So we gained three days.

1374
00:48:44,127 --> 00:48:46,226
What was more important than gaining three days...

1375
00:48:46,227 --> 00:48:47,837
was that it allowed South Korean forces to withdraw.

1376
00:48:48,867 --> 00:48:50,667
At the time, a large number of South Korean soldiers...

1377
00:48:51,237 --> 00:48:54,067
moved on their own, armed or unarmed,

1378
00:48:54,267 --> 00:48:55,807
to rejoin their units.

1379
00:48:56,537 --> 00:49:00,707
From here, they began to fall back.

1380
00:49:01,517 --> 00:49:03,616
The army wasn't destroyed.

1381
00:49:03,617 --> 00:49:06,487
More than half of the force survived and withdrew.

1382
00:49:07,747 --> 00:49:10,616
(The patriotism of the soldiers who continued to fight...)

1383
00:49:10,617 --> 00:49:13,486
(as they withdrew south of the Han River)

1384
00:49:13,487 --> 00:49:16,056
So they regrouped wherever they could...

1385
00:49:16,057 --> 00:49:17,756
and continued to fight again and again.

1386
00:49:17,757 --> 00:49:20,127
(They regrouped wherever they could and fought.)

1387
00:49:20,427 --> 00:49:22,967
Most other armies would have collapsed at this point.

1388
00:49:24,297 --> 00:49:27,366
But the plan of destroying the South Korean forces...

1389
00:49:27,367 --> 00:49:29,276
and then moving south through undefended territory...

1390
00:49:29,277 --> 00:49:31,137
went awry.

1391
00:49:34,147 --> 00:49:37,746
(The North's plan was stalled by the persistent resistance.)

1392
00:49:37,747 --> 00:49:39,847
Then the US forces began to join the war.

1393
00:49:40,317 --> 00:49:43,556
This is when Task Force Smith was deployed to Osan,

1394
00:49:43,557 --> 00:49:47,057
but it was the least trained unit among all US forces back then.

1395
00:49:47,927 --> 00:49:50,257
Japan was a land of ease for them,

1396
00:49:50,527 --> 00:49:53,097
so the US troops stationed there weren't training at all.

1397
00:49:53,427 --> 00:49:56,867
They were just spending their days pressing their uniforms.

1398
00:49:57,397 --> 00:49:59,037
So they couldn't fight properly.

1399
00:50:00,067 --> 00:50:04,107
That's why they were severely pushed back by the North.

1400
00:50:04,377 --> 00:50:07,947
They kept advancing south like that. But what's important is...

1401
00:50:08,517 --> 00:50:10,276
that involvement of US forces...

1402
00:50:10,277 --> 00:50:12,047
managed to buy us an extra day of time.

1403
00:50:12,517 --> 00:50:14,187
We got extra three days here,

1404
00:50:14,387 --> 00:50:17,416
and then got an extra day here, here, and here.

1405
00:50:17,417 --> 00:50:18,557
(Our forces were pushed back, buying time one day at a time.)

1406
00:50:18,827 --> 00:50:22,227
By July 24, the front line had been pushed back to the Nakdong River.

1407
00:50:22,727 --> 00:50:25,026
The North Korean forces also lost...

1408
00:50:25,027 --> 00:50:27,297
more than half of their troops while advancing this far.

1409
00:50:28,267 --> 00:50:31,066
Moreover, as their supply lines stretched too far,

1410
00:50:31,067 --> 00:50:34,137
they became targets for bombing, leading to their disruption.

1411
00:50:34,607 --> 00:50:36,336
So the Nakdong River defensive line,

1412
00:50:36,337 --> 00:50:39,307
spanning about 240 kilometers, was established here.

1413
00:50:39,507 --> 00:50:41,817
Here, 40 percent of the US forces,

1414
00:50:42,647 --> 00:50:44,717
the South Korean forces, which had only half its strength remaining,

1415
00:50:45,017 --> 00:50:47,586
and the North Korean forces, which lost 40 percent of forces...

1416
00:50:47,587 --> 00:50:50,857
had a desperate battle here.

1417
00:50:51,017 --> 00:50:54,086
In an unpredictable war like this, however,

1418
00:50:54,087 --> 00:50:55,327
tactical cohesion is bound to fall apart.

1419
00:50:56,257 --> 00:50:58,426
- I can imagine.
- So, in a war movie,

1420
00:50:58,427 --> 00:50:59,597
we often see this classic scene.

1421
00:50:59,867 --> 00:51:02,767
When a unit is cornered, someone suddenly begins a speech.

1422
00:51:02,967 --> 00:51:04,437
They roar like this...

1423
00:51:04,737 --> 00:51:07,037
and charge straight into the enemy lines.

1424
00:51:07,137 --> 00:51:08,477
If you fight like that, you're bound to lose.

1425
00:51:10,477 --> 00:51:11,477
(Sad)

1426
00:51:11,478 --> 00:51:14,147
Then, the North Korean forces launched simultaneous offensives...

1427
00:51:14,307 --> 00:51:15,517
across the entire front.

1428
00:51:16,017 --> 00:51:17,477
They just needed to break through at one point.

1429
00:51:17,717 --> 00:51:20,016
The UN and South Korean forces were short on troops,

1430
00:51:20,017 --> 00:51:21,247
so they lacked any second line of defense.

1431
00:51:21,787 --> 00:51:23,416
The front was as fragile as paper,

1432
00:51:23,417 --> 00:51:25,056
so they wanted a single breakthrough.

1433
00:51:25,057 --> 00:51:26,456
(The North Korean forces' goal was a single breakthrough.)

1434
00:51:26,457 --> 00:51:29,056
And many student soldiers were deployed there,

1435
00:51:29,057 --> 00:51:31,327
but they didn't even have helmets.

1436
00:51:31,997 --> 00:51:33,226
(The situation on the front lines was so dire...)

1437
00:51:33,227 --> 00:51:34,596
(that there was no time to properly train new recruits, )

1438
00:51:34,597 --> 00:51:36,036
(including student soldiers.)

1439
00:51:36,037 --> 00:51:37,796
(They were sent directly to the front...)

1440
00:51:37,797 --> 00:51:39,706
(after receiving only 3 or 4 hours...)

1441
00:51:39,707 --> 00:51:41,906
(of basic rifle marksmanship and grenade throwing instruction.)

1442
00:51:41,907 --> 00:51:43,736
I heard from someone...

1443
00:51:43,737 --> 00:51:45,577
who worked on recovering the remains of fallen soldiers.

1444
00:51:45,847 --> 00:51:48,617
The North Korean troops at least had helmets and canteens.

1445
00:51:49,217 --> 00:51:51,387
And they had deep trenches...

1446
00:51:51,617 --> 00:51:52,847
because they had shovels.

1447
00:51:53,247 --> 00:51:56,117
But the South Korean forces had neither helmets nor canteens.

1448
00:51:56,787 --> 00:51:59,757
Since they didn't have shovels, they couldn't dig proper trenches.

1449
00:52:00,357 --> 00:52:02,096
They had to claw at the earth with their bare hands,

1450
00:52:02,097 --> 00:52:03,827
so they were lying in shallow pits only 10cm deep.

1451
00:52:04,397 --> 00:52:07,026
They were forced to fight on the unprotected ground.

1452
00:52:07,027 --> 00:52:09,037
(The soldiers fought their best despite the dire circumstances.)

1453
00:52:09,637 --> 00:52:12,506
It was July and August, and the hills were bare.

1454
00:52:12,507 --> 00:52:13,967
They didn't even have shovels to dig trenches,

1455
00:52:14,337 --> 00:52:16,407
so they had no choice but to leave the bodies where they fell.

1456
00:52:17,237 --> 00:52:19,747
The corpses began to decompose within a single day.

1457
00:52:19,847 --> 00:52:22,477
Later, all the mountains were covered with rotting corpses.

1458
00:52:23,277 --> 00:52:24,577
They couldn't even approach the corpses.

1459
00:52:33,127 --> 00:52:35,856
In such horrific conditions,

1460
00:52:35,857 --> 00:52:37,697
the battles continued for about two weeks.

1461
00:52:37,957 --> 00:52:40,026
The North Korean forces were severely undersupplied,

1462
00:52:40,027 --> 00:52:42,397
and they had already exhausted a large number of troops.

1463
00:52:42,997 --> 00:52:44,836
So, between late July and early August,

1464
00:52:44,837 --> 00:52:46,667
they launched a desperate final offensive.

1465
00:52:47,367 --> 00:52:50,106
It is commonly believed that Nakdong River Defense Line...

1466
00:52:50,107 --> 00:52:52,647
held firm until the tide was turned by the Incheon Landing.

1467
00:52:53,407 --> 00:52:58,246
(Chapter 3. Incheon Landing and the Advance to North)

1468
00:52:58,247 --> 00:53:00,387
(Operation Chromite)

1469
00:53:00,547 --> 00:53:03,887
(Incheon Landing Operation)

1470
00:53:04,757 --> 00:53:06,926
(By launching an offensive in the central Korean Peninsula...)

1471
00:53:06,927 --> 00:53:10,057
(to sever the North's supply lines, )

1472
00:53:10,757 --> 00:53:14,066
(they launched a northward advance from the Nakdong River.)

1473
00:53:14,067 --> 00:53:17,067
The Incheon Landing took place on September 15.

1474
00:53:17,267 --> 00:53:20,536
In fact, by September 14,

1475
00:53:20,537 --> 00:53:23,077
the North Korean forces around there were already in a state of collapse.

1476
00:53:24,337 --> 00:53:26,406
So a northward advance from the Nakdong River...

1477
00:53:26,407 --> 00:53:29,577
could have been possible even without the operation.

1478
00:53:30,077 --> 00:53:32,646
Then you might think we didn't need the Incheon Landing.

1479
00:53:32,647 --> 00:53:33,817
But here's what's important.

1480
00:53:34,247 --> 00:53:37,456
If we had simply pushed them back while they were retreating,

1481
00:53:37,457 --> 00:53:40,886
the cost in civilian lives on our way back...

1482
00:53:40,887 --> 00:53:43,257
would have been astronomical.

1483
00:53:44,227 --> 00:53:47,197
An occupying army often acts with restraint,

1484
00:53:48,097 --> 00:53:50,936
as they intend to govern the territory.

1485
00:53:50,937 --> 00:53:54,407
But when they are forced to flee, they become ruthless.

1486
00:53:56,107 --> 00:53:58,206
If we had simply pushed northward from here without it,

1487
00:53:58,207 --> 00:54:00,106
- the civilian casualties...
- It could've been a disaster.

1488
00:54:00,107 --> 00:54:01,407
would have been ten times higher than what actually occurred.

1489
00:54:02,017 --> 00:54:05,817
The trauma of such a catastrophe would still be felt today.

1490
00:54:06,617 --> 00:54:09,417
The Incheon Landing must be viewed with this point in mind.

1491
00:54:09,557 --> 00:54:12,087
It's more important than a turning point in the war.

1492
00:54:13,127 --> 00:54:15,756
(By landing in Incheon and striking the enemy's rear...)

1493
00:54:15,757 --> 00:54:18,027
(to sever their supply lines, )

1494
00:54:18,727 --> 00:54:21,396
(the UN and South Korean forces at the Nakdong River...)

1495
00:54:21,397 --> 00:54:23,837
(started launching a vigorous northward advance.)

1496
00:54:24,067 --> 00:54:25,967
Our forces went up like this and severed the North's supply lines.

1497
00:54:26,437 --> 00:54:29,977
The North Korean forces lost 80 percent of their troops here.

1498
00:54:30,337 --> 00:54:33,076
It completely turned the tide of the war.

1499
00:54:33,077 --> 00:54:34,777
(Turning the tide of the war at a terrifying speed, )

1500
00:54:35,477 --> 00:54:37,916
(South Korea regained its heart, Seoul, in just 3 months.)

1501
00:54:37,917 --> 00:54:41,556
With the success of the Incheon Landing,

1502
00:54:41,557 --> 00:54:44,257
the second phase of the war at the Nakdong River came to an end.

1503
00:54:44,557 --> 00:54:45,957
Now it's the third phase.

1504
00:54:46,687 --> 00:54:47,726
The US ordered that the war be concluded...

1505
00:54:47,727 --> 00:54:48,797
at the pre-existing 38th parallel.

1506
00:54:49,197 --> 00:54:50,826
But, from South Korea's perspective,

1507
00:54:50,827 --> 00:54:52,767
the nation had already been divided.

1508
00:54:53,127 --> 00:54:55,697
So they insisted on pushing further north.

1509
00:54:55,797 --> 00:54:57,797
The US was concerned...

1510
00:54:58,437 --> 00:55:02,136
that further advancement would provoke the Soviet Union here.

1511
00:55:02,137 --> 00:55:05,506
And with the establishment...

1512
00:55:05,507 --> 00:55:07,406
of the People's Republic of China in 1949,

1513
00:55:07,407 --> 00:55:10,046
two major socialist powers were standing...

1514
00:55:10,047 --> 00:55:11,376
behind North Korea.

1515
00:55:11,377 --> 00:55:13,287
The US feared that if they clashed with these two countries,

1516
00:55:13,417 --> 00:55:15,086
it could escalate into a World War.

1517
00:55:15,087 --> 00:55:16,717
It could be as serious as a World War.

1518
00:55:17,117 --> 00:55:20,087
So they tried to stop our forces.

1519
00:55:20,357 --> 00:55:23,927
But, fueled by their momentum, they pressed on and advanced.

1520
00:55:24,297 --> 00:55:26,997
So, when was the first day they crossed the 38th parallel?

1521
00:55:27,227 --> 00:55:28,566
- October 1.
- It was October 1.

1522
00:55:28,567 --> 00:55:30,936
That is why October 1st was designated as Armed Forces Day.

1523
00:55:30,937 --> 00:55:32,666
They crossed the 38th parallel on October 1...

1524
00:55:32,667 --> 00:55:34,337
and advanced northward.

1525
00:55:34,767 --> 00:55:37,807
It felt as though reunification was within our reach.

1526
00:55:38,647 --> 00:55:40,376
However, as the situation turned dire for them,

1527
00:55:40,377 --> 00:55:41,406
North Korea brought in...

1528
00:55:41,407 --> 00:55:42,917
- the Chinese forces.
- Right. The Chinese forces.

1529
00:55:43,417 --> 00:55:45,516
Simply put, about 200,000 troops...

1530
00:55:45,517 --> 00:55:47,717
across 18 divisions entered the war.

1531
00:55:48,487 --> 00:55:52,757
This marked the beginning of a whole new phase in the war.

1532
00:55:53,057 --> 00:55:54,526
This is the third chapter.

1533
00:55:54,527 --> 00:55:56,726
Intervention of the Chinese forces and the Third Battle of Seoul.

1534
00:55:56,727 --> 00:55:58,467
(Chapter 4. The Chinese forces and the 3rd Battle of Seoul)

1535
00:55:58,927 --> 00:56:00,926
General MacArthur’s command aimed...

1536
00:56:00,927 --> 00:56:02,967
to reach the border as quickly as possible...

1537
00:56:03,197 --> 00:56:05,137
before any Chinese intervention.

1538
00:56:05,807 --> 00:56:08,107
This led to an aggressive,

1539
00:56:08,307 --> 00:56:10,807
high-speed northward advance.

1540
00:56:11,777 --> 00:56:14,206
On October 26 at 2pm,

1541
00:56:14,207 --> 00:56:15,346
the vanguard platoon of the 1st Battalion,

1542
00:56:15,347 --> 00:56:17,077
7th Regiment, 6th Division...

1543
00:56:17,447 --> 00:56:20,217
reached Chosan and drew water from the Amnok River.

1544
00:56:20,387 --> 00:56:23,086
The water has been preserved to this day.

1545
00:56:23,087 --> 00:56:25,087
(The water collected in the canteen has been preserved to this day.)

1546
00:56:25,427 --> 00:56:28,526
But the Chinese forces were already swarming the area.

1547
00:56:28,527 --> 00:56:30,356
(The Chinese forces were lying in ambush on all sides.)

1548
00:56:30,357 --> 00:56:32,997
Actually, they were deeply intimidated by the US forces.

1549
00:56:33,127 --> 00:56:36,297
They had witnessed its power during the Second World War.

1550
00:56:36,397 --> 00:56:40,037
Back then, its industrial capacity was beyond imagination.

1551
00:56:40,237 --> 00:56:42,436
The US provided everything,

1552
00:56:42,437 --> 00:56:45,407
like hundreds of thousands of combat boots.

1553
00:56:45,707 --> 00:56:47,876
Therefore, the Chinese forces figured...

1554
00:56:47,877 --> 00:56:49,747
that they stood no chance against the US in a prolonged war.

1555
00:56:50,077 --> 00:56:51,687
Then, what should they do?

1556
00:56:52,087 --> 00:56:54,317
So, this is how the Chinese forces structured their tactics.

1557
00:56:55,417 --> 00:56:58,587
First, there was a tactic known as "stealth maneuver."

1558
00:56:59,157 --> 00:57:02,226
It is said that the MacArthur command ignored...

1559
00:57:02,227 --> 00:57:04,626
reports of Chinese intervention back then,

1560
00:57:04,627 --> 00:57:06,267
but that's not the case.

1561
00:57:07,027 --> 00:57:09,237
They actually doubled their aerial reconnaissance.

1562
00:57:09,567 --> 00:57:12,867
But, back then, the Korean landscape was comprised of barren hills,

1563
00:57:12,967 --> 00:57:14,307
and it was winter.

1564
00:57:14,707 --> 00:57:17,077
There were only snowy fields without trees.

1565
00:57:17,337 --> 00:57:19,576
They believed the movement of 200,000 troops...

1566
00:57:19,577 --> 00:57:22,616
would inevitably leave some paths or traces.

1567
00:57:22,617 --> 00:57:25,116
They would have to feed the 200,000 soldiers...

1568
00:57:25,117 --> 00:57:26,487
and distribute supplies.

1569
00:57:26,817 --> 00:57:29,887
They figured that it was impossible to evade aerial surveillance.

1570
00:57:30,417 --> 00:57:32,357
So they continued to conduct aerial reconnaissance,

1571
00:57:32,657 --> 00:57:34,487
but found no traces of the enemy.

1572
00:57:34,927 --> 00:57:36,957
(Strange)

1573
00:57:37,597 --> 00:57:39,126
They covered themselves...

1574
00:57:39,127 --> 00:57:40,666
- in white blankets...
- Right. White blankets.

1575
00:57:40,667 --> 00:57:42,667
and brushed the snow back over their tracks.

1576
00:57:43,067 --> 00:57:45,937
The 200,000 soldiers moved without a trace.

1577
00:57:46,507 --> 00:57:49,177
This was the first terrifying aspect that the US failed...

1578
00:57:49,307 --> 00:57:50,476
to anticipate.

1579
00:57:50,477 --> 00:57:53,776
And a military unit doesn't simply advance in war.

1580
00:57:53,777 --> 00:57:56,017
So, the command post is here. When they advance,

1581
00:57:56,077 --> 00:57:58,247
they establish guard posts and supply bases here.

1582
00:57:58,487 --> 00:57:59,986
And frontline units are positioned ahead.

1583
00:57:59,987 --> 00:58:01,547
When paths diverge,

1584
00:58:02,387 --> 00:58:03,816
they branch out like this.

1585
00:58:03,817 --> 00:58:05,187
(The South Korean forces had a thorough advancement plan.)

1586
00:58:05,387 --> 00:58:08,996
However, the Chinese forces were already lying in ambush around them.

1587
00:58:08,997 --> 00:58:10,157
(The Chinese forces were already lying in ambush.)

1588
00:58:10,297 --> 00:58:11,726
It was surrounded by mountains.

1589
00:58:11,727 --> 00:58:12,966
(Hiding in the mountains surrounding the area)

1590
00:58:12,967 --> 00:58:14,666
They were lying here in ambush.

1591
00:58:14,667 --> 00:58:16,267
And the US forces moved along the roads.

1592
00:58:17,067 --> 00:58:18,766
They waited until our forces were within the territory,

1593
00:58:18,767 --> 00:58:21,777
and launched a coordinated attack simultaneously on the set date.

1594
00:58:22,537 --> 00:58:24,436
The number of troops must have been enormous.

1595
00:58:24,437 --> 00:58:26,476
- They had 200,000 soldiers.
- About 200,000 soldiers.

1596
00:58:26,477 --> 00:58:29,117
Back then, the US forces had about 50,000 soldiers.

1597
00:58:29,477 --> 00:58:32,216
The Chinese forces attacked with their full strength.

1598
00:58:32,217 --> 00:58:34,917
It is known as "human wave tactics."

1599
00:58:35,617 --> 00:58:38,427
They mobilized a massive volume of personnel and resources.

1600
00:58:38,927 --> 00:58:40,956
That's how they seized...

1601
00:58:40,957 --> 00:58:42,856
the key areas here.

1602
00:58:42,857 --> 00:58:46,597
Then the forward combat units were completely isolated.

1603
00:58:47,327 --> 00:58:49,437
So, the units here were forced to retreat.

1604
00:58:49,767 --> 00:58:51,397
The Chinese forces attacked them as they retreated here.

1605
00:58:52,207 --> 00:58:54,337
And they attacked another retreating unit here.

1606
00:58:54,637 --> 00:58:56,337
And the supply lines were cut off.

1607
00:58:56,577 --> 00:58:58,077
The artillery was neutralized.

1608
00:58:58,677 --> 00:59:01,277
The Chinese leadership thought that by annihilating UN forces...

1609
00:59:01,577 --> 00:59:03,146
using this tactic,

1610
00:59:03,147 --> 00:59:04,176
they could incite anti-war sentiment in the US.

1611
00:59:04,177 --> 00:59:06,716
They wouldn't want to die in another county's war.

1612
00:59:06,717 --> 00:59:08,917
They expected anti-war sentiment like this.

1613
00:59:09,217 --> 00:59:11,057
Once the US forces were forced to retreat,

1614
00:59:11,317 --> 00:59:14,687
they would isolate and annihilate South Korean forces.

1615
00:59:14,887 --> 00:59:16,956
But there's a famous story from this campaign.

1616
00:59:16,957 --> 00:59:20,126
The first Marine Division of the US forces. broke out.

1617
00:59:20,127 --> 00:59:21,367
(The 1st Marine Division successfully escaped from the trap.)

1618
00:59:22,037 --> 00:59:23,596
(The 1st Marine Division was surrounded and attacked...)

1619
00:59:23,597 --> 00:59:25,366
(by Chinese forces more than ten times their own size.)

1620
00:59:25,367 --> 00:59:27,566
First Marine Division escaped...

1621
00:59:27,567 --> 00:59:29,976
through a famous battle called the Battle of Lake Changjin.

1622
00:59:29,977 --> 00:59:31,236
(Battle of Lake Changjin: 1st Marine Division withdraws.)

1623
00:59:31,237 --> 00:59:33,906
They escaped and reached Hungnam...

1624
00:59:33,907 --> 00:59:34,976
to carry out the famous operation we know,

1625
00:59:34,977 --> 00:59:37,316
- Hungnam Evacuation.
- Hungnam Evacuation.

1626
00:59:37,317 --> 00:59:38,816
(Hungnam Evacuation: UN Forces evacuated with 100,000 evacuees.)

1627
00:59:38,817 --> 00:59:42,157
We wonder how they evacuated, right?

1628
00:59:42,787 --> 00:59:44,016
As they say, there is always a way out.

1629
00:59:44,017 --> 00:59:46,487
I'd like to add an explanation to that photo.

1630
00:59:46,787 --> 00:59:49,026
That's a photo of the withdrawal.

1631
00:59:49,027 --> 00:59:52,467
The mountains were full of the Chinese People's Volunteers.

1632
00:59:52,767 --> 00:59:55,566
However, on the right was a plain.

1633
00:59:55,567 --> 00:59:56,636
(The opposite side was a plain.)

1634
00:59:56,637 --> 00:59:59,466
If there are mountains on both sides,

1635
00:59:59,467 --> 01:00:01,236
Chinese People's Volunteers can attack.

1636
01:00:01,237 --> 01:00:05,147
But the soldiers could catch a break in the open.

1637
01:00:05,647 --> 01:00:08,077
According to the locals,

1638
01:00:08,407 --> 01:00:10,577
the mountains were full of the Chinese People's Volunteers.

1639
01:00:11,077 --> 01:00:13,417
Nevertheless, First Marine Division escaped...

1640
01:00:13,647 --> 01:00:14,816
and the US forces promoted it.

1641
01:00:14,817 --> 01:00:17,317
"Look, our marines survived."

1642
01:00:17,617 --> 01:00:20,286
Because of that, the US didn't have anti-war sentiment.

1643
01:00:20,287 --> 01:00:21,426
(The US didn't have anti-war sentiment.)

1644
01:00:21,427 --> 01:00:22,427
Then...

1645
01:00:22,757 --> 01:00:25,427
Chinese People's Volunteers' field commanders went,

1646
01:00:25,827 --> 01:00:28,967
"This is bad. We should've captured them."

1647
01:00:29,437 --> 01:00:31,136
"Since we failed to capture them,"

1648
01:00:31,137 --> 01:00:33,967
"we won't be able to beat the US in the long run."

1649
01:00:34,207 --> 01:00:37,137
So they suggested a negotiation.

1650
01:00:37,537 --> 01:00:39,706
But Mao Zedong felt like they had a chance to win.

1651
01:00:39,707 --> 01:00:41,046
They had won before.

1652
01:00:41,047 --> 01:00:42,146
So he pushed through.

1653
01:00:42,147 --> 01:00:43,776
(Mao Zedong pushed the forces to advance to the south.)

1654
01:00:43,777 --> 01:00:46,616
Then Chinese People's Volunteers' weakness became known eventually.

1655
01:00:46,617 --> 01:00:48,116
Since they relied on...

1656
01:00:48,117 --> 01:00:50,086
draining their manpower during the battles,

1657
01:00:50,087 --> 01:00:51,256
they couldn't fight for more than a week.

1658
01:00:51,257 --> 01:00:52,426
(Weakness 1, Physical exhaustion)

1659
01:00:52,427 --> 01:00:53,557
And all their tactics were known.

1660
01:00:53,987 --> 01:00:55,427
Do you know what happened once?

1661
01:00:55,827 --> 01:00:58,227
Chinese People's Volunteers weren't very flexible.

1662
01:00:58,827 --> 01:01:01,266
On the first day, the human wave attack...

1663
01:01:01,267 --> 01:01:03,067
wiped out half of the UN forces.

1664
01:01:03,567 --> 01:01:06,137
Then they should've been wiped out after five days, right?

1665
01:01:06,807 --> 01:01:08,676
But by the second day, they could figure out the route...

1666
01:01:08,677 --> 01:01:10,037
of the Chinese People's Volunteers.

1667
01:01:10,877 --> 01:01:12,807
After a while, they understood so much...

1668
01:01:13,247 --> 01:01:15,617
that they could attack where their enemies were hiding.

1669
01:01:16,047 --> 01:01:17,617
The next day, the enemies gathered at the same place.

1670
01:01:18,117 --> 01:01:19,516
Hold on.

1671
01:01:19,517 --> 01:01:21,616
During the week-long battle,

1672
01:01:21,617 --> 01:01:23,416
Chinese People's Volunteers took the same route at the same time.

1673
01:01:23,417 --> 01:01:24,787
UN forces could sleep easily because of that.

1674
01:01:25,427 --> 01:01:27,286
- The enemies stuck to that time.
- They came at the same time.

1675
01:01:27,287 --> 01:01:28,556
- For goodness' sake.
- They could set the alarm.

1676
01:01:28,557 --> 01:01:29,956
- My goodness.
- Gosh.

1677
01:01:29,957 --> 01:01:31,526
- Because of that, - I can't believe it.

1678
01:01:31,527 --> 01:01:33,866
- UN forces dominated...
- They were simple-minded.

1679
01:01:33,867 --> 01:01:38,166
in terms of tactics over time despite losing many soldiers.

1680
01:01:38,167 --> 01:01:42,336
The US had air supremacy and firepower,

1681
01:01:42,337 --> 01:01:45,307
so the UN forces decided to bait their enemies.

1682
01:01:46,147 --> 01:01:48,076
"If we stay here, they'll come..."

1683
01:01:48,077 --> 01:01:49,946
- "through the route..."
- Yes.

1684
01:01:49,947 --> 01:01:51,046
"they've taken before."

1685
01:01:51,047 --> 01:01:52,417
"Let's drop bombs on them then."

1686
01:01:52,787 --> 01:01:54,916
They baited their enemies and bombed them.

1687
01:01:54,917 --> 01:01:56,457
Through such tactics,

1688
01:01:56,957 --> 01:02:00,787
UN forces began to win the battles.

1689
01:02:01,187 --> 01:02:02,826
Thus, they recaptured Seoul.

1690
01:02:02,827 --> 01:02:05,397
(They pushed forward and recaptured Seoul.)

1691
01:02:06,027 --> 01:02:08,166
(They reached the 38th parallel in 3 days.)

1692
01:02:08,167 --> 01:02:09,337
When that happened,

1693
01:02:09,497 --> 01:02:12,167
the field commanders of Chinese People's Volunteers said,

1694
01:02:12,667 --> 01:02:15,336
"This won't work. Let's give up."

1695
01:02:15,337 --> 01:02:16,736
Now comes the last chapter...

1696
01:02:16,737 --> 01:02:19,346
after the fourth one, ceasefire talks.

1697
01:02:19,347 --> 01:02:20,347
Ceasefire.

1698
01:02:20,348 --> 01:02:22,147
(Chapter 5, Ceasefire Talks and the Hill Battle)

1699
01:02:22,347 --> 01:02:24,016
After Chinese People's Volunteers reached a stalemate,

1700
01:02:24,017 --> 01:02:25,416
a location in Kaesong was chosen...

1701
01:02:25,417 --> 01:02:27,416
- for the ceasefire talks.
- Ceasefire.

1702
01:02:27,417 --> 01:02:29,587
But the Chinese People's Volunteers dragged on the ceasefire talks.

1703
01:02:30,217 --> 01:02:32,486
They suggested establishing...

1704
01:02:32,487 --> 01:02:35,127
a Military Demarcation Line on the 38th parallel...

1705
01:02:35,597 --> 01:02:36,826
for the ceasefire.

1706
01:02:36,827 --> 01:02:39,627
But since the UN forces were advancing to the north,

1707
01:02:39,897 --> 01:02:43,397
they suggested establishing it at the point of cessation.

1708
01:02:44,097 --> 01:02:46,006
If we study the Chinese documents,

1709
01:02:46,007 --> 01:02:47,967
they knew that it'd be established...

1710
01:02:48,237 --> 01:02:51,277
at the current point of cessation of hostilities.

1711
01:02:51,677 --> 01:02:53,706
But they decided to draw out the process...

1712
01:02:53,707 --> 01:02:57,377
to acquire as much land as possible.

1713
01:02:57,717 --> 01:02:59,616
The UN forces' command ordered...

1714
01:02:59,617 --> 01:03:02,817
to defend only and refrain from attacking.

1715
01:03:03,117 --> 01:03:04,356
But here is the funny thing.

1716
01:03:04,357 --> 01:03:07,027
As you know, our nation is full of mountains.

1717
01:03:07,427 --> 01:03:09,297
The funniest thing happened during the war.

1718
01:03:09,957 --> 01:03:12,726
From the hill that was higher than the hill the soldiers were on,

1719
01:03:12,727 --> 01:03:14,596
enemies shot at them. What then?

1720
01:03:14,597 --> 01:03:16,396
Defending from the current hill got them nowhere.

1721
01:03:16,397 --> 01:03:18,366
- Right. They had to go up.
- They had to capture that hill.

1722
01:03:18,367 --> 01:03:19,566
- When they did that, - Right.

1723
01:03:19,567 --> 01:03:20,906
they found a higher hill.

1724
01:03:20,907 --> 01:03:21,966
(Ho Dong Hill after Shin Young Hill)

1725
01:03:21,967 --> 01:03:23,277
This is a famous story.

1726
